    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Cornopteris parvisora improperly include experiencing nausea, develop diarrhea, experiencing headaches, experiencing vomiting, and experiencing stomach pain. These adverse reactions are often caused by consuming excessive amounts of the plant, which can lead to gastrointestinal irritation and inflammation. The toxic compounds present in Cornopteris parvisora, such as alkaloids and glycosides, can also cause nausea and vomiting by irritating the stomach and intestines. In severe cases, improper use of Cornopteris parvisora can lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalances due to excessive vomiting and diarrhea. It is essential to consult with a medical professional or a qualified botanist before using Cornopteris parvisora for medicinal purposes to avoid these side effects.",
    "uses": "Cornopteris parvisora is a species of fern, however, information on its medicinal uses is limited. It is traditionally used in some Asian cultures for its purported health benefits, but its effectiveness and safety have not been extensively scientifically studied. Further research is needed to determine the potential medicinal properties of Cornopteris parvisora. In some traditional Chinese medicine practices, it is believed to have anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties. More studies are required to confirm these potential medicinal uses.",
    "taxonomy": "Cornopteris parvisora belongs to the family Polypodiaceae and order Polypodiales. It is a species of fern that is native to certain regions. The classification of Cornopteris parvisora places it within the kingdom Plantae, due to its characteristics as a vascular plant. Further classification includes its family and order, which are part of the larger division Pteridophyta. The genus Cornopteris is also part of the larger kingdom.",
    "benefits": "Cornopteris parvisora, also known as the Chinese maidenhair fern, has been traditionally used in Chinese medicine for its potential health benefits. It is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help alleviate symptoms of arthritis and other inflammatory conditions. The plant is also thought to possess antioxidant properties, which can help protect the body from oxidative stress and damage. Additionally, Cornopteris parvisora is believed to have cardiovascular benefits, as it may help lower blood pressure and improve overall cardiovascular health. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy of Cornopteris parvisora for these potential health benefits.",
    "parts": "Cornopteris parvisora, a species of fern, is known to have various medicinal properties. The rhizomes of Cornopteris parvisora are used in traditional medicine for their purported anti-inflammatory and antiseptic effects. The plant's leaves and stems are also used in some herbal remedies to treat various health issues. The rhizomes are typically dried and crushed to create a powder that can be used to treat wounds and skin conditions. However, it is essential to note that the efficacy and safety of using Cornopteris parvisora for medicinal purposes have not been extensively scientifically studied or validated.",
    "intro": "Cornopteris parvisora is a species of flowering plant in the family Polypodiaceae, commonly known as a type of fern. Traditionally, this plant has been used to treat various health conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and digestive issues, due to its anti-inflammatory and antipyretic properties. The bioactive constituents of Cornopteris parvisora include flavonoids, alkaloids, and phenolic acids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In herbal medicine, Cornopteris parvisora is often used to make teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are used to treat a range of health problems, including colds, flu, and joint pain."
